abstract: KANSAS CITY, MO. LONG after the 77th World Series has been re  duced to a set of numbers in a book and memory has lost the image of Willie Mays Aikens's standing at the plate like stout Cor  tez watching his home-run blasts whistle out toward the waterfalls in Royals Stadium, one picture will remain vivid.

SPARKILL, N.Y.  SOMETHING shocking and horrible, and yet wonderful, is going on at the Dominican Convent in this Rockland County town just  a few miles work of the New Jersey border. This reviewer, at least, is shocked when he discovers a brilliantly original work of art by an artist of whom he has never heard that is harrowing in its philosophical and political content.

abstract: KANSAS CITY, Oct. 18--In the losers' locker room beneath Royals Stadium today, Mike Schmidt said after the Philadelphia Phillies' 5-3 loss to the Kansas City Royals: "It's not like starting the World Series over again. We are precisely starting the World Series over again."

abstract: Ray Terilli, a junior halfback, rushed for 82 yards and two touchdowns as Roxbury handed Livingston its first loss of the season yesterday, 27-8, in Succasunna.

KANSAS CITY, Mo. WHEN Frank White Jr. was 19 years old and playing base  ball in a Ban Johnson League here, scouts from every team in the major leagues were unanimous: He was swift afoot and sure afield and he would never hit the size of his hat.

abstract: UNIVERSITY PARK, Pa., Oct. 18-- Football teams that combine intelligent running with an aggressive pass rush usually win. Penn State, the ranking college team in the East, combined those ingredients today in a methodical 24-7 victory over Syracuse.

abstract: KANSAS CITY, Mo., Oct. 18--The fuse that Kansas City's American League champions belatedly lighted 13 hours earlier burned even brighter for the Royals today when they defeated the Philadelphia Phillies, 5-3, and tied the World Series at two games each.
